{"amendments":[{"body":"`src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:431-442` and `src/adapters/fs.rs:2815-2832` unconditionally reuse a sole legacy running row (`run_id == None`) when a new start arrives with `run_id = Some(...)`. That is safe for idempotent repair, but it is wrong for a real retry after upgrade: a stale pre-upgrade open row and a genuinely new run get merged into one attempt, because the old row is backfilled instead of appending a second `TaskRunEntry`. This loses retry history and violates the requirement that bead attempts remain auditable by run.","rationale":"Backward-compat handling should not erase distinct retries. A fresh run ID is exactly the signal that a new attempt may exist, but the current adapter rewrites history instead of preserving it."},{"body":"`src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:302-310` plus `src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:465-490` make the no-`run_id` path depend on `started_at` uniqueness. Distinct attempts in the same `project_id` are considered the same attempt whenever their timestamps match, and terminal rows with the same outcome are then collapsed into one history entry. Because `run_id` is explicitly optional for backward compatibility, this means two retries can disappear from `find_runs_for_bead` if the caller reuses or truncates timestamps, which breaks the acceptance criterion that multiple retries remain visible.","rationale":"The new audit query should not rely on timestamp precision to preserve retry history. In the backward-compatible path, the current collapse rule can silently drop repeated attempts."}],"summary":"Reviewed the milestone lineage/model/fs changes end-to-end and ran `cargo test milestone_record` successfully. I found two correctness/auditability issues, both in the backward-compat path when `run_id` is absent or being backfilled."}